Deutsch-Jozsa Algorithm Explorer

The Core Problem:
Given a function f: {0,1}^n → {0,1}, determine if it's:
•	CONSTANT: f always returns 0 or always returns 1
•	BALANCED: f returns 0 for exactly half the inputs, 1 for the other half
Classical vs Quantum:
Classical: Up to 2^(n-1) + 1 evaluations
  n=1:    2 evaluations
  n=10:   513 evaluations  
  n=100:  2^99 (impossible!)

Quantum: Exactly 1 evaluation (always!)
  Any n: Just 1 oracle call
6 Core Experiments:
1.	Function Properties — Understanding constant vs balanced
2.	1-Qubit Deutsch — Simple case (4 possible functions)
3.	2-Qubit DJ — Testing multiple constant and balanced functions
4.	3-Qubit DJ — 8 inputs, 256 possible functions (tests a few)
5.	Complexity Analysis — Shows exponential speedup scaling
6.	Oracle Construction — How to encode functions into quantum gates
Key Algorithm Steps:
1.	Superposition all inputs + ancilla in |−⟩
2.	Apply oracle U_f (phase-encodes the function)
3.	Hadamard interference reveals the property
4.	Measure: All 0s = CONSTANT, Any 1 = BALANCED
Why It Works:
•	Classical: Must check each input individually
•	Quantum: Interference pattern reveals GLOBAL property in one shot
•	Oracle phase-flips paths where f(x)=1
•	Hadamard interference amplifies the pattern
Visualizations (5 PNG files):
•	1-qubit, 2-qubit, 3-qubit function classifications
•	Exponential complexity comparison (log scale)
•	Algorithm flow diagram (initialization → oracle → measurement)
To Run:
bash
python DeutschJozsaExplorer.py

This demonstrates real quantum advantage—the first algorithm showing computers can be exponentially faster! It's the precursor to Shor's factoring algorithm.

